<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="209" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="209">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="209">
The specific epithet &quot; 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="209">multicaulis</emphasis>
&quot; refers to the new species having many ascending stems that are branched in the middle and upper parts.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="209" type="phenology">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="209">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="209">This new species was found in flowering from middle June (in a field trip in 2006) to August and in fruiting from July to September.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="209" type="pollen morphology">
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="209">Pollen morphology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="4" pageNumber="209">
Pollen grains are radially symmetrical, isopolar, spheroidal and medium in size (polar length: 23.71-25.47 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
equatorial diameter: 18.86-20.29 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
). Pollen apertures are bisyncolpate (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Field photos and pollen of Pedicularis multicaulis W. B. Yu, H. Wang &amp; D. Z. Li A-C overview of habitat and plants D inflorescence E flowers F infructescence G equatorial view of pollen H polar view of pollen I exine ornamentation." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.130.35258.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/327940" pageId="4" pageNumber="209">Figures 2G and H</figureCitation>
) and the colpi are usually wide and sunken (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Field photos and pollen of Pedicularis multicaulis W. B. Yu, H. Wang &amp; D. Z. Li A-C overview of habitat and plants D inflorescence E flowers F infructescence G equatorial view of pollen H polar view of pollen I exine ornamentation." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.130.35258.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/327940" pageId="4" pageNumber="209">Figure 2G</figureCitation>
); exine ornamentation is perforated tectum with microfoveolate ornamentation (
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Field photos and pollen of Pedicularis multicaulis W. B. Yu, H. Wang &amp; D. Z. Li A-C overview of habitat and plants D inflorescence E flowers F infructescence G equatorial view of pollen H polar view of pollen I exine ornamentation." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.130.35258.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/327940" pageId="4" pageNumber="209">Figure 2I</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
